  <section id="disease">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-amber-400 mb-4">§7 — Disease Mapping: What Ultra-High Resolution Reveals</h2>
    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
      <div class="bg-kernel-900 border border-kernel-700 rounded-lg p-5">
        <h3 class="text-xs font-bold text-red-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-3">Alzheimer's Disease</h3>
        <div class="text-xs text-kernel-400 space-y-2">
          <p><strong class="text-kernel-200">Primary targets:</strong> Hippocampus CA1 (F=0.740), CA2/3, amygdala lateral &amp; basal</p>
          <p><strong class="text-kernel-200">Secondary:</strong> Temporal cortex, cingulate cortex, fornix</p>
          <p><strong class="text-kernel-200">Key finding:</strong> CA1 subfield neurodegeneration is the earliest
            detectable marker. Standard 1mm³ MRI cannot resolve CA1 from CA2/3.
            Ultra-high resolution (0.125 mm³) resolves 7 hippocampal subfields,
            enabling 35% detection gain over standard MRI.</p>
          <p class="text-kernel-500 italic">Detection gain from subfields: <span class="text-red-400">+35%</span></p>
        </div>
        <div class="mt-3 grid grid-cols-4 gap-1" id="ad-targets"></div>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-kernel-900 border border-kernel-700 rounded-lg p-5">
        <h3 class="text-xs font-bold text-purple-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-3">Parkinson's Disease</h3>
        <div class="text-xs text-kernel-400 space-y-2">
          <p><strong class="text-kernel-200">Primary targets:</strong> Substantia nigra (F=0.680), red nucleus, subthalamic nucleus</p>
          <p><strong class="text-kernel-200">Secondary:</strong> Putamen, caudate, globus pallidus</p>
          <p><strong class="text-kernel-200">Key finding:</strong> Deep gray matter nuclei volume loss precedes
            motor symptoms by years. These nuclei are only identifiable with
            ultra-high resolution — pBrain achieves Dice = 0.89 for deep GM.</p>
          <p class="text-kernel-500 italic">Detection gain from subfields: <span class="text-purple-400">+40%</span></p>
        </div>
        <div class="mt-3 grid grid-cols-3 gap-1" id="pd-targets"></div>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-kernel-900 border border-kernel-700 rounded-lg p-5">
        <h3 class="text-xs font-bold text-amber-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-3">Frontotemporal Dementia</h3>
        <div class="text-xs text-kernel-400 space-y-2">
          <p><strong class="text-kernel-200">Primary targets:</strong> Frontal cortex (F=0.730), temporal cortex, insular cortex</p>
          <p><strong class="text-kernel-200">Secondary:</strong> Amygdala lateral, cingulate cortex</p>
          <p><strong class="text-kernel-200">Key finding:</strong> MRI-based anatomical staging (Planche 2023)
            can track disease progression through cortical volume patterns.
            Large cortical structures have lower resolution_dependence — FTD is
            more detectable with standard resolution than other dementias.</p>
          <p class="text-kernel-500 italic">Detection gain from subfields: <span class="text-amber-400">+25%</span></p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-kernel-900 border border-kernel-700 rounded-lg p-5">
        <h3 class="text-xs font-bold text-cyan-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-3">Multiple Sclerosis</h3>
        <div class="text-xs text-kernel-400 space-y-2">
          <p><strong class="text-kernel-200">Primary targets:</strong> Corpus callosum (F=0.638), corticospinal tract, cerebellar WM</p>
          <p><strong class="text-kernel-200">Secondary:</strong> Arcuate fasciculus, uncinate fasciculus, pons</p>
          <p><strong class="text-kernel-200">Key finding:</strong> WMn (White Matter nulled) modality specifically
            enhances white matter lesion detection. Standard T1w/T2w miss many
            periventricular lesions. This is HoliAtlas's unique advantage —
            first atlas with synthetic WMn.</p>
          <p class="text-kernel-500 italic">Detection gain from subfields: <span class="text-cyan-400">+30%</span></p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-kernel-900 border border-kernel-700 rounded-lg p-5">
        <h3 class="text-xs font-bold text-yellow-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-3">Epilepsy</h3>
        <div class="text-xs text-kernel-400 space-y-2">
          <p><strong class="text-kernel-200">Primary targets:</strong> Hippocampus CA1 (F=0.740), CA2/3, amygdala lateral &amp; basal</p>
          <p><strong class="text-kernel-200">Secondary:</strong> Temporal cortex, insular cortex, thalamus</p>
          <p><strong class="text-kernel-200">Key finding:</strong> Mesial temporal sclerosis — the most common
            surgical epilepsy substrate — presents as CA1 volume loss with
            relative CA2/3 sparing. Ultra-high resolution resolves this
            differential pattern. The Papez circuit (hippocampus → fornix →
            mammillary → thalamus → cingulate) shows correlated IC depression
            during seizure propagation, detectable as synchronized drift across
            the circuit.</p>
          <p class="text-kernel-500 italic">Detection gain from subfields: <span class="text-yellow-400">+42%</span></p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-kernel-900 border border-kernel-700 rounded-lg p-5">
        <h3 class="text-xs font-bold text-orange-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-3">Huntington's Disease</h3>
        <div class="text-xs text-kernel-400 space-y-2">
          <p><strong class="text-kernel-200">Primary targets:</strong> Caudate nucleus (F=0.710), putamen (F=0.700), globus pallidus</p>
          <p><strong class="text-kernel-200">Secondary:</strong> Insular cortex, frontal cortex, cingulate cortex</p>
          <p><strong class="text-kernel-200">Key finding:</strong> Striatal volume loss (caudate + putamen) is the
            hallmark biomarker. The kernel reveals that striatal degeneration
            propagates along the reward pathway (VTA → nucleus accumbens →
            caudate / putamen), with IC dropping geometrically across the
            chain — a direct instance of geometric slaughter (§3 orientation).
            Caudate volume loss up to 10 years before motor onset.</p>
          <p class="text-kernel-500 italic">Detection gain from subfields: <span class="text-orange-400">+38%</span></p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-kernel-900 border border-kernel-700 rounded-lg p-5">
        <h3 class="text-xs font-bold text-emerald-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-3">ALS (Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis)</h3>
        <div class="text-xs text-kernel-400 space-y-2">
          <p><strong class="text-kernel-200">Primary targets:</strong> Motor cortex (F=0.730), corticospinal tract (F=0.640), pons</p>
          <p><strong class="text-kernel-200">Secondary:</strong> Medulla oblongata, cerebellar white matter, frontal cortex</p>
          <p><strong class="text-kernel-200">Key finding:</strong> Upper and lower motor neuron degeneration
            traces the motor pathway (motor cortex → corticospinal tract →
            pons → medulla). The kernel detects this as progressive fidelity
            loss along the pathway with the white-matter segments (WM)
            showing the steepest drift. DTI-enabled resolution is critical —
            WMn modality reveals demyelination invisible on T1w.</p>
          <p class="text-kernel-500 italic">Detection gain from subfields: <span class="text-emerald-400">+33%</span></p>
